Some easyJet passengers have faced chaos in the last week. A group of British tourists told Express.co.uk how they were left stranded in Montenegro after their flights were cancelled. READ MORE: Flight attendant says Starbucks is 'easiest way' to get free upgrade    easyJet has cancelled hundreds of flights in the last few weeks due to staffing issues and other problems. All passengers are entitled to an alternative flight to their destination if there is one available. This is the case even if the only available flight is on a rival airline to easyJet. Passengers with short notice cancellations could also be entitled to cash compensation. Passengers won’t receive cash compensation if an airline can justify that the flight was cancelled due to “extraordinary circumstances”. British tourists could face a summer of travel misery as airline and airport issues could be set to continue. Passengers have had to deal with chaotic scenes at UK airports including at Bristol and Manchester. Tourists have been photographed queuing outside the airport due to lengthy security queues inside. Britons are advised to check the status of their flight before travelling to the airport.